Helen Branswell@HelenBranswell (https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell)
#Ebola: 3 more cases today & 4 deaths (1 in the community) bring the outbreak totals to 542 confirmed & probable cases & 319 deaths. This outbreak is staggeringly large in context where nearly 50 000 doses of vaccine have been administered.

2. Speaking of the #Ebola vaccine, it's really nice to see that its use in the North Kivu outbreak made @voxdotcom's list of top science stories of the year. Some great scientists working at Canada's National Lab made that vaccine.

[See 18 Dec 2018. The Ebola vaccine is tested in a war zone
[Vox, edited]
https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2018/12/18/18134579/top-science-news-2018
[byline: Brian Resnick, Julia Belluz, Umair Irfan, Eliza Barclay]

An ongoing Ebola outbreak in a war-torn region of the Democratic Republic of Congo is already the 2nd-largest Ebola outbreak in history, with more than 500 cases. But amid the tragedy and chaos, public health officials have accomplished a remarkable feat: For the 1st time in history, an experimental Ebola vaccine is being rolled out at a large scale, potentially preventing infections and saving lives.

Merck's rVSV-ZEBOV is the 1st highly effective Ebola vaccine. But because of a lack of pharmaceutical company interest, it literally sat on a shelf until it was licensed to Merck in 2014.

It wasn't until this year [2018] that the vaccine was used in an ongoing outbreak. Public health officials have managed to get more than 45 000 people vaccinated as of this writing. And as Peter Salama, the head of the new Health Emergencies Program at the World Health Organization, told Vox, health officials are achieving between 95 and 100 per cent coverage. Those are the levels we see for vaccination coverage of well-tested shots in stable and wealthy countries. So, this Ebola vaccine rollout in a war zone is something to celebrate.]

[The vaccine was created by scientists at the National Microbiology Laboratory in Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada, which is part of the Public Health Agency of Canada (PHAC). PHAC licensed it to NewLink Genetics, which started developing the vaccine; NewLink in turn licensed it to Merck in 2014. - Mod.LK]

- Mon 17 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=089b5462c7

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 16 Dec 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 539, of which 491 are confirmed and 48 are probable. In total, there have been 315 deaths (267 in confirmed and 48 in probable cases) and 186 people have recovered.
- 75 suspected cases under investigation.
- 8 new confirmed cases, 3 in Katwa, 2 in Butembo, 2 in Komanda, and 1 in Oicha.
- 2 new confirmed case deaths in Katwa.
- 2 new recoveries released from Butembo ETC.

News of the response
Youth and sport
---------------
- The last phases of the football [soccer] tournament 'Ebola Pas Chez Moi' [Ebola not in my house] started this Mon 17 Dec 2018 with the final and the 3rd place playoff in Butembo. After 2 weeks of strong emotions, it was the 'Racing Club of Kivu' (RCK) team that won the title of tournament champion in Butembo after having imposed on penalties against the team 'Jeunesse Sportive de Butembo '(JSB). The RCK will face Beni's championship team in the Grand Final of the tournament and attempt to win the Cup of Hope this Thu 20 Dec 2018.
- The coordination of the Ebola response organized this football tournament in Beni and Butembo in order to build trust with the youth of both cities. It was observed that young people were often the source of reluctance in the community and the 1st perpetrators of destruction of sanitary materials. The aim of the football tournament was to appease this youth, raise awareness about Ebola and invite them to take ownership of the Ebola response to end the epidemic.
- Throughout the tournament, many awareness activities were organized. Community animators animated the games with messages and awareness songs. After being trained on the disease and the means of prevention, the young players themselves became involved in raising public awareness by recording prevention messages that were also broadcast by local radio stations. A special prize was awarded to the player of the tournament voted best sensitizer of the competition. Handwashing and temperature sensing devices were installed at the entrance to all stadiums. Moreover, on the sidelines of the final in Butembo, experts on the different pillars of the Ebola response were set up in booths and answered all the public's questions about the epidemic.

Vaccination
-----------
- Continued wide-belt vaccination (or ring plus) in Otomaber (in Komanda Health Zone) and Aloya (in Mabalako Health Zone).
- Continued immunization of primary care providers in the Goma health zone.
- Since vaccination began on 8 August 2018, 48 048 people have been vaccinated, including 19 017 in Beni [North Kivu], 8619 in Katwa [North Kivu], 5077 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 4974 in Butembo [North Kivu], 2208 in Kalunguta [North Kivu], 1663 in Mandima [Ituri], 824 in Komanda [Ituri], 791 in Vuhovi [North Kivu], 750 in Masereka [North Kivu], 700 in Lubero [North Kivu], 670 in Oicha [North Kivu], 607 in Kyondo [North Kivu], 599 in Mutwanga [North Kivu], 434 in Bunia [Ituri], 355 in Tchomia [Ituri], 344 in Musienene [North Kivu], 257 in Goma [North Kivu], 70 in Biena [North Kivu], 63 in Alimbongo [North Kivu], 13 in Karisimbi [North Kivu], and 13 in Kisangani [Tshopo].

- Sun 16 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
