communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This outbreak has been particularly hard on babies and healthcare workers. The toll of any disease is not easy to accept, but the Ebola outbreaks are particularly heartbreaking. According to this report, children are believed to make up about a third of all cases of people being infected, with experts warning they catch it from parents and medical centres. 53 healthcare workers have contracted Ebola, 18 of whom have died. Both losses are large. - Mod.LK]

******
[4] Tragedy
Date: Tue 18 Dec 2018
Source: UN OCHA, ReliefWeb, World Food Programme report [edited]
https://reliefweb.int/report/democratic-republic-congo/wfp-driver-killed-democratic-republic-congo


The World Food Programme [WFP] is deeply saddened by the killing on Mon [17 Dec 2018] of a staff member in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). A driver was shot dead during an ambush by unknown assailants about 70 kilometres [43.5 mi] north west of Goma, North Kivu province, while travelling by road with 3 colleagues to monitor a food distribution. His WFP companions were unhurt in the attack, which occurred at 8.30 am local time in the Loashi area of Masisi territory. Their vehicle was headed for Nyabiondo, where the distribution, to 13 000 people recently displaced by violence, was to take place.

Armed groups, many of them criminal gangs who prey on local communities and travellers, are active in North Kivu, particularly Masisi territory. They are also known to disrupt the work of humanitarian organisations.

"As we mourn our dear friend, we condemn this senseless killing and urge all parties to ensure safe passage for humanitarian staff engaged in life-saving work", said WFP DRC country director Claude Jibidar, who had known the deceased for almost 20 years. [The deceased] leaves behind a wife and 9 children, aged between 3 and 23. He joined WFP in 1995 and was admired and respected by colleagues for his professionalism, decency, and calm. "I never, ever heard him complain", said Makena Walker, the head of WFP's office in Goma, North Kivu's capital, where he was based.

DRC is one of the world's most complex, challenging, and dangerous humanitarian environments. As is the case in such places, humanitarian, and other workers operating there often put their lives on the line, travelling long distances through areas where insecurity is rife. They do so with little thought for their own safety, in the service of those less fortunate than themselves. [The deceased] was one such person, who chose to serve his fellow countrymen with selflessness and dedication. He is fondly remembered by his family, his friends and his colleagues.

The United Nations World Food Programme -- saving lives in emergencies and changing lives for millions through sustainable development. WFP works in more than 80 countries around the world, feeding people caught in conflict and disasters, and laying the foundations for a better future.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This is truly a tragedy on several fronts, including the loss of a dedicated individual conducting a humanitarian mission, the loss of a father to 9 children and a husband to his wife. The group that targeted the WFP truck is known to specifically "disrupt the work of humanitarian organisations." This is about as despicable an act as anything could be. - Mod.LK

